The `Timer` and `TimerTask` classes were supplanted by the Executors framework added to Java 5. This fact is noted in the Javadoc for those classes.

An [`ExecutorService`][1] object will process one or more tasks in one or more background threads. 

You seem to have two goals in mind. 

 - Run a series of tasks in order.
 - Halt the processing of further tasks upon some flag.

Both can be accomplished with an executor service. 

For the first, use a single-threaded executor service. With only a single thread at its disposable, the executor service schedules each task to run one after another, in the order in which they were submitted.

For the second, I would signal a flag via an `AtomicBoolean` object, with your tasks written to look for them. With a single instance of `AtomicBoolean`, initialized before you set up your executor service, then reading and writing to the contained boolean value is [thread-safe][2].

Let&#39;s take an example task that loops a few times, pretending each time to do some work which we simulate by sleeping the thread.

```java
package work.basil.example.vthreads;

import java.time.Duration;
import java.time.Instant;
import java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService;
import java.util.concurrent.Executors;
import java.util.concurrent.ThreadLocalRandom;
import java.util.concurrent.atomic.AtomicBoolean;

public class SeriesOfTasks
{
    public static void main ( String[] args )
    {
        SeriesOfTasks app = new SeriesOfTasks ( );
        app.demo ( );
    }

    private void demo ( )
    {
        System.out.println ( &quot;INFO - Demo starting. &quot; + Instant.now ( ) );
        final AtomicBoolean keepGoingFlag = new AtomicBoolean ( true );
        try (
                ExecutorService executorService = Executors.newSingleThreadScheduledExecutor ( ) ;
        )
        {
            executorService.submit ( new TellTime ( &quot;A&quot; , keepGoingFlag ) );
            executorService.submit ( new TellTime ( &quot;B&quot; , keepGoingFlag ) );
            executorService.submit ( new TellTime ( &quot;C&quot; , keepGoingFlag ) );
            try { Thread.sleep ( Duration.ofSeconds ( 20 ) ); } catch ( InterruptedException e ) { throw new RuntimeException ( e ); }
            keepGoingFlag.set ( false );
            executorService.submit ( new TellTime ( &quot;D&quot; , keepGoingFlag ) );
        }
        System.out.println ( &quot;INFO - Demo ending. &quot; + Instant.now ( ) );
    }
}

class TellTime implements Runnable
{
    private final String id;
    private final AtomicBoolean continueFlag;

    public TellTime ( final String id , final AtomicBoolean continueFlag )
    {
        this.id = id;
        this.continueFlag = continueFlag;
    }

    @Override
    public void run ( )
    {
        for ( int ordinal = 1 ; ordinal &lt;= 3 ; ordinal++ )
        {
            if ( this.continueFlag.get ( ) )
            {
                int seconds = ThreadLocalRandom.current ( ).nextInt ( 1 , 3 );
                try { Thread.sleep ( Duration.ofSeconds ( seconds ) ); } catch ( InterruptedException e ) { throw new RuntimeException ( e ); }
                System.out.println ( &quot;Task &quot; + this.id + &quot; ordinal &quot; + ordinal + &quot; in thread id &quot; + Thread.currentThread ( ).threadId ( ) + &quot; says the time is &quot; + Instant.now ( ) );
            } else
            {
                System.out.println ( &quot;Task &quot; + this.id + &quot; ordinal &quot; + ordinal + &quot; in thread id &quot; + Thread.currentThread ( ).threadId ( ) + &quot; found the flag set to FALSE at &quot; + Instant.now ( ) );
                break;   // Else exit this loop.
            }
        }
    }
}
```

